Has there ever been a pure liquidity problem at a crypto firm? Like what I =
have in mind is this:
=09A crypto firm owes $100 (in crypto I guess) to somebody (customers, lend=
ers) who can demand their money back on short notice.=09The firm has $200 w=
orth of stuff (crypto assets I guess).=C2=A0=09The customers or lenders dem=
and their $100 back all at once.=09The firm=E2=80=99s $200 worth of stuff i=
s not immediately accessible for some reason: It is in long-term crypto-den=
ominated mortgages, say. Or it is in locked crypto tokens. Or it is in cryp=
to tokens and there is, for some reason, a temporary lack of liquidity in t=
he market for those tokens. Or it is a large quantity of some crypto token =
that could be sold for $200 over the course of a week or two, but if you se=
ll it in an hour or two =E2=80=94=C2=A0to give people their money back all =
at once =E2=80=94=C2=A0that will crash the price.=09The firm cannot raise $=
100 to pay back its customers or lenders, and implodes.=09But it had $200 w=
orth of stuff! Very unfair.

This, to be clear, is the=C2=A0standard=C2=A0story of bank runs in traditio=
nal banking. It is the Diamond-Dybvig model that won a Nobel Memorial Prize=
 this year. The standard problem is =E2=80=9Cthe assets are good but long-t=
erm, and the customers want their money now.=E2=80=9D It is the problem tha=
t central banks are set up to solve. The solution is fairly straightforward=
: You have a central bank with lots of money (ideally, in modern central ba=
nking, the ability to print money). If a bank with good assets is facing a =
liquidity crunch, it can go to the central bank and say =E2=80=9Cwe have $2=
00 of assets but we can=E2=80=99t get $100 of cash, help,=E2=80=9D and the =
central bank will help. It will help by =E2=80=9Clending freely, against go=
od collateral, at a penalty rate,=E2=80=9D as  Bagehot=E2=80=99s famous for=
mula goes: The central bank will lend the bank $100 to pay its depositors, =
but first it will make sure that the bank really has $200 of good stuff. (A=
nd it will charge interest.) If a bank shows up at the Federal Reserve and =
says =E2=80=9Chi we owe depositors $100 but don=E2=80=99t have it, we lost =
it all on roulette,=E2=80=9D the Fed will not help.
  [1]

Meanwhile in crypto I just don=E2=80=99t hear a lot of stories like that? I=
 am not saying it is impossible, or even that unlikely; I am just saying th=
at I=E2=80=99ve never really heard of it happening. Oh I mean I have heard =
many many stories, in crypto, that have the same rough shape, =E2=80=9Crun =
on the bank=E2=80=9D stories. But the ones I have heard are all subtly diff=
erent. They go like this:
=09A crypto firm owes $100 to customers or lenders.=09The firm=E2=80=99s ba=
lance sheet shows $200 worth of stuff.=09Somebody notices that the $200 wor=
th of stuff is just a piece of paper with the words =E2=80=9Cthis is worth =
$200=E2=80=9D scrawled on it in crayon, and points that out online.=09The c=
ustomers or lenders read this and, sensibly, demand their $100 back all at =
once.=09The firm tries to shop its scrawled piece of paper to raise the $10=
0, and gets bids for it of zero dollars.=09The firm cannot raise $100 to pa=
y back its customers or lenders,=C2=A0and implodes.=09But it had $0 worth o=
f stuff, so this seems like a pretty reasonable result, though of course ba=
d for customers.

In other words, every crypto liquidity crisis story that I have heard is=C2=
=A0obviously a solvency crisis. The problem is not that the firm has good a=
ssets but cannot, for some reason, convert them quickly into ready money. T=
he problem is that the firm has bad assets and people notice and demand the=
ir money back and the money isn=E2=80=99t there. The reasons the money isn=
=E2=80=99t there will vary. Sometimes the firm just lost money on risky tra=
des. Sometimes the money all went into magic beans and the magic bean marke=
t collapsed. (This is the story of   TerraUSD and Luna.) Sometimes the mone=
y was stolen by hackers, or by the firm=E2=80=99s executives, or both.
But the story is never =E2=80=9Cthis crypto firm took demand deposits and u=
sed them to fund 30-year mortgages, and while those mortgages are still pay=
ing and are likely to be money-good, the firm doesn=E2=80=99t have the cash=
 right now.=E2=80=9D Because that is, uh, not really how crypto works? Comp=
ared to banks, crypto firms probably have a bit more carelessness and fraud=
, but they=C2=A0definitely=C2=A0have  a lot more magic beans. Crypto firms =
tend to have assets that do not have cash flows, and that are highly correl=
ated to=C2=A0confidence in crypto=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0often highly correlat=
ed to=C2=A0confidence in that firm itself=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and so when t=
hey lose confidence they also tend to lose their assets.
Anyway  here=E2=80=99s a tweet from Changpeng =E2=80=9CCZ=E2=80=9D Zhao, th=
e chief executive officer of Binance Holdings Ltd.:
To reduce further cascading negative effects of FTX, Binance is forming an =
industry recovery fund, to help projects who are otherwise strong, but in a=
 liquidity crisis. More details to come soon. In the meantime, please conta=
ct Binance Labs if you think you qualify.
The most notable liquidity crisis in crypto this year was at FTX.com, the b=
ig crypto exchange founded by Sam Bankman-Fried. And when FTX needed money =
for customer withdrawals, it   went to Binance for a bailout. And Binance a=
greed to rescue FTX, subject to due diligence. And then Binance did like 15=
 minutes of due diligence and   said absolutely not, and   the deal fell ap=
art. Because it is pretty obvious that FTX is not =E2=80=9Cotherwise strong=
, but in a liquidity crisis=E2=80=9D: FTX is in a solvency crisis, in which=
 the customer money is mostly gone and   what=E2=80=99s left is mostly wort=
hless beans.=C2=A0
Several of the other most notable liquidity crises in crypto this year were=
 at firms that were themselves bailed out by FTX and Alameda Research, a he=
dge fund that was also founded by Bankman-Fried and that was closely associ=
ated with FTX. For whatever reason, FTX and Alameda do not seem to have   c=
oncerned themselves too much with whether the firms they were rescuing were=
 solvent.
  [2]
=C2=A0
It is possible that over the next few years there will be a Binance-led ind=
ustry recovery fund, and it will act like a central bank for crypto, and it=
 will lend freely, against good collateral, at penalty rates. And occasiona=
lly, in challenging markets, crypto projects that are otherwise strong, but=
 in a liquidity crisis, will come to the Central Binance Bank to borrow mon=
ey, and the Central Binance Bank will support them, and they will preserve =
long-term value. But if the Central Binance Bank had existed=C2=A0this=C2=
=A0year, how many projects would it have saved? Not FTX, anyway.

