      More FTX
   =20
 =20

That said, if you just=C2=A0wanted=C2=A0to have a liquidity crisis,  here=
=E2=80=99s one way to do it:

Meanwhile, at a meeting with Alameda employees on Wednesday, [Alameda CEO C=
aroline]=C2=A0Ellison explained what had caused the collapse, according to =
a person familiar with the matter. Her voice shaking, she apologized, sayin=
g she had let the group down. Over recent months, she said, Alameda had tak=
en out loans and used the money to make venture capital investments, among =
other expenditures.
Around the time the crypto market crashed this spring, Ms. Ellison explaine=
d, lenders moved to recall those loans, the person familiar with the meetin=
g said. But the funds that Alameda had spent were no longer easily availabl=
e, so the company used FTX customer funds to make the payments.=C2=A0

Yes, no, right, if you are a crypto hedge fund, and you take out short-term=
 loans, and you use those loans to=C2=A0make venture capital investments, t=
hen your loans will come due long before the time horizon of your venture i=
nvestments, and then I guess you=E2=80=99ll =E2=80=A6=C2=A0use customer mon=
ey from your affiliated exchange to repay the loans? What was the good way =
for this to go?
We   talked extensively yesterday about the crisis at FTX. The basic situat=
ion is:
=09FTX owes customers something like $9 billion.=09Its balance sheet =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0really the combined balance sheet of FTX, Alameda=C2=A0and various=
 affiliates =E2=80=94=C2=A0consists mostly of cobwebs and magic beans.=09Wh=
ere did the money go?

=E2=80=9CInto venture investments=E2=80=9D is only a very partial answer, s=
ince those venture investments=C2=A0are=C2=A0on  the balance sheet, at cost=
, totaling about $3 billion. I speculated on some other possibilities, with=
 the simplest being something like =E2=80=9CAlameda made leveraged bets on =
cryptocurrencies, lost money in volatile crypto markets, and took FTX custo=
mer money to pay back its loans.=E2=80=9D
But this is all very speculative and there are not a lot of facts available=
. You can find other explanations online, and I would like to link to some =
of them here, with heavy caveats.=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t want to vouch for th=
ese analyses, because they are speculative and sometimes anonymous and the =
facts remain murky. But I do want to summarize them, because they are inter=
esting and sort of rhyme with each other. Here is a  blog post from =E2=80=
=9CMilky Eggs=E2=80=9D on =E2=80=9CWhat happened at Alameda Research,=E2=80=
=9D and here are Twitter threads from  Tensai Capital and  Doug Colkitt.
Basically if you read these accounts, not necessarily focusing too much on =
specific hard-to-verify claims, the sense you will get is something like:
=09Alameda Research did a ton of trading on FTX. If you =E2=80=94=C2=A0a re=
gular person or a crypto hedge fund =E2=80=94=C2=A0came to FTX to trade, th=
ere=E2=80=99s a good chance you were trading against Alameda.=09Alameda was=
 not very good at trading. If you traded against Alameda on FTX, there=E2=
=80=99s a good chance you made money.

What exactly No. 2 means can vary. It could mean, like, on a market microst=
ructure level, Alameda did not have the best view of crypto prices, and so =
sophisticated high-frequency crypto traders could reliably make money tradi=
ng against it. (Colkitt: =E2=80=9CCrypto trading firms had the illusion the=
y were skilled. Instead all they were doing was winning against the Washing=
ton Generals.=E2=80=9D) But it could also be a story about FTX=E2=80=99s li=
quidation engine: Customers could make levered bets on cryptocurrencies on =
FTX and be automatically liquidated if the bets moved against them, and thi=
s liquidation seems to have consisted largely of Alameda buying their posit=
ions. This was a good experience for customers =E2=80=94=C2=A0it made betti=
ng on FTX more predictable and less risky =E2=80=94=C2=A0and possibly good =
for Alameda, if it bought stuff that went down and then the stuff went up a=
gain. But when the Luna token collapsed earlier this year, Alameda would (o=
n this theory) have been buying tons of Luna all the way down, leaving it w=
ith a huge stash of worthless Luna and a big loss.
But never mind the details; the point of this theory=C2=A0is that FTX offer=
ed a very good customer experience to traders =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you traded =
on FTX, you made money =E2=80=94=C2=A0at the expense of Alameda constantly =
losing money to those traders. And when money got too tight at Alameda, the=
 theory goes, FTX dipped into customer money to keep Alameda afloat.
If you believe some form of this theory, it is a mixed bag. On the one hand=
, doesn=E2=80=99t it sound sort of nice? FTX wasn=E2=80=99t dipping into cu=
stomer money to make wild speculative bets, or to pay for its executives=E2=
=80=99 lifestyles. It was just really committed to providing a good custome=
r experience, and that is expensive, and so it ended up running at a loss, =
and unfortunately it dipped into customer money to subsidize that loss. The=
 other good news, on this theory, is that the answer to the question =E2=80=
=9Cwhere did the money go=E2=80=9D would be =E2=80=9Cmostly back to the cus=
tomers=E2=80=9D: Some customers=E2=80=99 funds were lost, but they went bac=
k to other customers in the form of trading gains.
On the other hand,=C2=A0there is a technical name, in law and finance, for =
this sort of thing. It is a bad name. When you have a business that takes m=
oney from some customers and uses it to generate trading gains for other cu=
stomers, that=E2=80=99s just, I am sorry, a Ponzi scheme. I am not sure it=
=E2=80=99s worse than any other explanation of what happened =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0in any case, the customer money is missing! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=
=99s not=C2=A0good.
In other FTX news, the Wall Street Journal  reports that =E2=80=9CFTX filed=
 for bankruptcy last week, but the cryptocurrency exchange=E2=80=99s founde=
r still thinks that he can raise enough money to make users whole, accordin=
g to people familiar with the matter. Mr. Bankman-Fried, alongside a few re=
maining employees, spent the past weekend calling around in search of commi=
tments from investors to plug a shortfall of up to $8 billion in the hopes =
of repaying FTX=E2=80=99s customers, the people said.=E2=80=9D I really do =
not understand what investors would be getting for their $8 billion but I g=
uess I hope it works? I hope he=E2=80=99s calling the Binance fund.
And FTX=E2=80=99s  chaotic bankruptcy filing means we still don=E2=80=99t h=
ave much in the way of information from FTX about what happened, though tha=
t is starting to change a little bit. Here is  a motion filed by FTX in its=
 bankruptcy case yesterday; it isn=E2=80=99t very interesting, honestly, bu=
t it does have this short version of the collapse:
FTX faced a severe liquidity crisis that necessitated the filing of these c=
ases on an emergency basis last Friday. Questions arose about Ml. Bankman-F=
ried's leadership and the handling of FTX's complex array of assets and bus=
inesses under his direction. As the situation became increasingly dire, Sul=
livan & Cromwell and =C3=83lvarez & Marsal North America, LLC ("Alvarez & M=
arsal") were engaged to provide restructuring advice and services to FTX. A=
t approximately 4:30 a.m. on Friday, November 11, after consultation with h=
is own legal counsel, Mr. Bankman-Fried ultimately agreed to step aside, re=
sulting in the appointment of John J. Ray III, an experienced restructuring=
 executive, as Chief Executive Officer.
And the New York Times reports that Bankman-Fried =E2=80=9Chas also found o=
ther ways to occupy his time in recent days, playing the video game Storybo=
ok Brawl, though less than he usually does,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=A6=C2=A0doi=
ng weird tweets?

Shortly before the interview, Mr. Bankman-Fried had posted a cryptic tweet:=
 the word =E2=80=9CWhat.=E2=80=9D Then he had tweeted the letter H. Asked t=
o explain, Mr. Bankman-Fried said he planned to post the letter A and then =
the letter P. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s going to be more than one word,=E2=80=
=9D he said. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m making it up as I go.=E2=80=9D
So he was planning a series of cryptic tweets? =E2=80=9CSomething like that=
.=E2=80=9DBut why? =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=
=9CI=E2=80=99m improvising. I think it=E2=80=99s time.=E2=80=9D

By noon today he got through =E2=80=9CWhat H-A-P-P-E-N-E-D,=E2=80=9D follow=
ed by a legal disclaimer and =E2=80=9CI'll get to what happened. But for no=
w, let's talk about where we are today.=E2=80=9D

