   =20
      Greenleasing
   =20
 =20

If I were a young person looking for a place to start a career in finance, =
one niche that I might consider is ESG Consultant But Evil. A lot of big co=
mpanies and investors these days are looking for ways to improve their envi=
ronmental, social and governance ratings, and a lot of them will go to vari=
ous sorts of ESG consultants who will tell them how to cut emissions or wha=
tever. But some of them will go to ESG Consultants But Evil, who will sort =
of sneak in through the back door and say =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99ve got som=
e=C2=A0carbon credits that fell off a truck, I=E2=80=99ll sell =E2=80=99em =
to you for 20 cents on the dollar.=E2=80=9D Lots of people want to go into =
ESG to save the world, so that is a competitive business. Getting into ESG =
for the financial engineering seems pretty interesting and possibly less cr=
owded.
Possibly more crowded though. Here are  Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Sheryl Tia=
n Tong Lee and Stephen Stapczynski=C2=A0last week:=C2=A0

One of Singapore=E2=80=99s best-performing stocks this year =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
an energy company backed by state investor=C2=A0Temasek Holdings Pte=C2=A0=
=E2=80=94 is=C2=A0under fire for trying to avoid higher interest payments t=
o bondholders that kick in if the company fails to meet=C2=A0emissions targ=
ets.
In order to reduce its official carbon footprint,=C2=A0Sembcorp Industries =
Ltd.=C2=A0sold two coal-fired power plants to an Omani group for $1.5 billi=
on. The company told shareholders that the sale would lower its=C2=A0greenh=
ouse gas=C2=A0emissions intensity=C2=A0by 38%, more than enough to dodge th=
e penalties attached to the company=E2=80=99s=C2=A0sustainability-linked bo=
nds.
But the firm financed the sale=C2=A0=C2=A0of the assets with a 15-year loan=
=C2=A0and retains =E2=80=9Csubstantial=E2=80=9D liabilities and =E2=80=9Cop=
erational influence,=E2=80=9D over the business, according to a report by=
=C2=A0Anthropocene Fixed Income Institute, a London-based think tank. That =
effectively makes Sembcorp a shadow bank for the coal industry, Anthropocen=
e argues, and=C2=A0the carbon footprint of the coal plants shouldn=E2=80=99=
t be removed until the loan is fully repaid.=C2=A0
Sembcorp, in which Temasek=C2=A0holds a 49% stake, has two outstanding=C2=
=A0sustainability-linked bonds=C2=A0totaling S$975 million ($697=C2=A0milli=
on).=C2=A0Under the performance targets, the company has to pay an extra 25=
 basis points in interest if it failed to meet the emissions intensity targ=
ets.
The sale of the coal plants is =E2=80=9Cpurely a greenwashing exercise,=E2=
=80=9D said=C2=A0Kelvin Law, an associate professor of accounting at Singap=
ore=E2=80=99s Nanyang Technological University. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s the s=
ame facilities, same group of employees, same polluting activities, just un=
der a different name.=E2=80=9D

I=E2=80=99m sorry, I know I=E2=80=99m a monster, but I love it so much? The=
 point here is that =E2=80=9Ccarbon footprint=E2=80=9D is an=C2=A0accountin=
g regime, a set of conventions. Certain sorts of companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0b=
ig public companies with ESG-focused investors, big companies that borrow f=
rom big banks using sustainability-linked bonds, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0are se=
nsitive to carbon accounting. The more carbon emissions are on their carbon=
 accounting statement, the worse off they are. Other sorts of companies =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0Middle Eastern sovereign wealth funds, Russian oligarchs, etc. =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0are less sensitive, or insensitive, to carbon accounting. No=
body looks at their carbon accounting statements, nobody cares, they can po=
llute as much as they want.
So if you are a carbon-sensitive company, you find a carbon-insensitive com=
pany, and you park your carbon on its balance sheet. And you pay it some fe=
e for the service, which is presumably less than you=E2=80=99re saving on y=
our sustainability bonds or whatever. It is the purest sort of financial en=
gineering, transferring this abstract cost to the cheapest bearer of the co=
st.
Just! Imagine being=C2=A0the banker who shows up at the energy company that=
 is trying to get rid of coal, and being like =E2=80=9CI have a way to get =
rid of your coal for you,=E2=80=9D and they are like =E2=80=9Cis it wind po=
wer,=E2=80=9D and you are like =E2=80=9Coh no, we=E2=80=99re gonna get a no=
velty oversized fake mustache and glue it on the front of your coal plants =
so we can pretend they=E2=80=99re someone else=E2=80=99s coal plants.=E2=80=
=9D ESG Consulting But Evil. It=E2=80=99s perfect, I love it, no notes.
Oh, I can=E2=80=99t resist, one note. The trade here is that you have someo=
ne for whom=C2=A0carbon emissions are expensive, and you arrange a trade to=
 park its emissions with a counterparty who is indifferent to emissions, fo=
r a fee.=C2=A0Great trade, fantastic, but you could do better. What you rea=
lly want is a counterparty who wants to=C2=A0increase its emissions. You wa=
nt a counterparty who will boast, like,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe are on track to em=
it more carbon this year than we ever have before, we are the world leaders=
 in pollution,=E2=80=9D because it gets some economic=C2=A0benefit=C2=A0fro=
m increasing emissions.=C2=A0Ideally you want one side of the trade who wil=
l=C2=A0pay to get rid of emissions, and the other side who will=C2=A0pay to=
 take on emissions, and you =E2=80=94=C2=A0the ESG Consultant But Evil who =
arranges the trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0take a fee from both sides.=C2=A0
I feel like if you play your cards right you could find a few counterpartie=
s like that in Texas? It is not=C2=A0quite=C2=A0the case that Texas has an =
alternative carbon-emissions accounting regime in which companies are penal=
ized for not emitting enough carbon. But it is=C2=A0a little bit=C2=A0the c=
ase. Right now big financial firms=C2=A0are=C2=A0facing financial penalties=
 in Texas for not doing enough fossil-fuel financing. Set up a Texas shell =
company, have it buy all the worst fossil-fuel projects from all the ESG-se=
nsitive companies around the world, have it produce=C2=A0insane amounts of =
carbon emissions, and then go to banks to be like =E2=80=9Cif you lend=C2=
=A0this=C2=A0company money then you will get a ton of credit in Texas for f=
ossil-fuel fifinancing.=E2=80=9D I have not worked this idea out fully. But=
 I bet someone will.

