   =20
      Where are the customers=E2=80=99 cars?
   =20
 =20

There is a surprisingly fruitful subfield of academic finance research abou=
t fund managers=E2=80=99 cars. We   talked a few years ago about  a paper f=
inding that =E2=80=9Chedge fund managers who own powerful sports cars take =
on more investment risk but do not deliver higher returns.=E2=80=9D And now=
  here is a paper =E2=80=94=C2=A0which shares three of its four authors wit=
h the powerful-sports-car one =E2=80=94=C2=A0about how =E2=80=9Cmutual fund=
 managers increase investment allocations to companies manufacturing automo=
biles they have purchased.=E2=80=9D If you drive a Ferrari you will take mo=
re risk for fewer returns; if you drive a Ford you=E2=80=99ll buy stock in =
Ford. Also:

We then examine why fund managers tend to overweight companies whose produc=
ts they consume and find satisfactory in their portfolio. Among retail inve=
stors, a leading explanation that has been proposed in=C2=A0 the literature=
 is behavioral biases related to familiarity or preferences. =E2=80=A6 Amon=
g professional investors, however, it would be surprising if this investmen=
t pattern is driven by the familiarity/preference bias, since these investo=
rs face higher costs from poor portfolio performance due, for example, to c=
areer concerns (Chevalier and Ellison, 1999b). As an alternative, we propos=
e that consumption experiences contain value-relevant information, which ma=
y serve as the basis for consumption-induced portfolio choices among invest=
ment fiduciaries. =E2=80=A6 Fortunately, these two channels (familiarity vs=
. informational advantage) can be empirically disentangled by examining the=
 performance of post-consumption positions, as the two channels lead to dif=
ferent performance implications. The familiarity/preference bias explanatio=
n predicts that consumption-induced positions should perform similarly to, =
if not worse than, other positions; the information-based explanation, on t=
he other hand, predicts that these positions should have superior performan=
ce.
Consistent with the information-based explanation, we find that after an au=
tomobile purchase, fund-managers=E2=80=99 positions in companies manufactur=
ing the purchased automobiles can better predict these manufacturers=E2=80=
=99 future stock returns.

If you drive a Ford and then buy Ford stock, you probably have a good reaso=
n, and the stock will go up. Somehow the paper does not mention Tesla.

