<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Has there ever been a pure liquidity problem a=
t a crypto firm? Like what I have in mind is this:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A crypto firm owes $100 (in crypto I g=
uess) to somebody (customers, lenders) who can demand their money back on s=
hort notice.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The firm has $200 wor=
th of stuff (crypto assets I guess).=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">The customers or lenders demand their $100 back all at once.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The firm=E2=80=99s $200 worth of stuff=
 is not immediately accessible for some reason: It is in long-term crypto-d=
enominated mortgages, say. Or it is in locked crypto tokens. Or it is in cr=
ypto tokens and there is, for some reason, a temporary lack of liquidity in=
 the market for those tokens. Or it is a large quantity of some crypto toke=
n that could be sold for $200 over the course of a week or two, but if you =
sell it in an hour or two =E2=80=94=C2=A0to give people their money back al=
l at once =E2=80=94=C2=A0that will crash the price.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">The firm cannot raise $100 to pay back its customers or l=
enders, and implodes.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But it had $=
200 worth of stuff! Very unfair.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This, to be clear, is the=C2=A0<em>standard=C2=
=A0</em>story of bank runs in traditional banking. It is the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29707590.273527/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53=
aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvRGlhbW9uZCVFMiU4MCU5M0R5YnZpZ19tb2RlbA/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB6240e167" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">Diamond-Dybvig model</a> that won a <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29707590.273527/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cubm9iZWxwcml6ZS5vcmcvcHJpemVzL2Vjb25vbWljLXNjaWVuY2VzLzIwMjIvc3VtbWFy=
eS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbfdafa8a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Nobel Memorial Prize</a> thi=
s year. The standard problem is =E2=80=9Cthe assets are good but long-term,=
 and the customers want their money now.=E2=80=9D It is the problem that ce=
ntral banks are set up to solve. The solution is fairly straightforward: Yo=
u have a central bank with lots of money (ideally, in modern central bankin=
g, the ability to <em>print </em>money). If a bank with good assets is faci=
ng a liquidity crunch, it can go to the central bank and say =E2=80=9Cwe ha=
ve $200 of assets but we can=E2=80=99t get $100 of cash, help,=E2=80=9D and=
 the central bank will help. It will help by =E2=80=9Clending freely, again=
st good collateral, at a penalty rate,=E2=80=9D as <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29707590.273527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmVkZXJhbH=
Jlc2VydmUuZ292L25ld3NldmVudHMvc3BlZWNoL21hZGlnYW4yMDA5MDgyMWEuaHRt/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cBe25e4e9a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Bagehot=E2=80=99s famous formula</a> go=
es: The central bank will lend the bank $100 to pay its depositors, but fir=
st it will make sure that the bank really has $200 of good stuff. (And it w=
ill charge interest.) If a bank shows up at the Federal Reserve and says =
=E2=80=9Chi we owe depositors $100 but don=E2=80=99t have it, we lost it al=
l on roulette,=E2=80=9D the Fed will not help.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile in crypto I just don=E2=80=99t hear =
a lot of stories like that? I am not saying it is impossible, or even that =
unlikely; I am just saying that I=E2=80=99ve never really heard of it happe=
ning. Oh I mean I have heard many many stories, in crypto, that have the sa=
me rough shape, =E2=80=9Crun on the bank=E2=80=9D stories. But the ones I h=
ave heard are all subtly different. They go like this:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A crypto firm owes $100 to customers o=
r lenders.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The firm=E2=80=99s bala=
nce sheet shows $200 worth of stuff.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">Somebody notices that the $200 worth of stuff is just a piece of paper w=
ith the words =E2=80=9Cthis is worth $200=E2=80=9D scrawled on it in crayon=
, and points that out online.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The =
customers or lenders read this and, sensibly, demand their $100 back all at=
 once.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The firm tries to shop its =
scrawled piece of paper to raise the $100, and gets bids for it of zero dol=
lars.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The firm cannot raise $100 t=
o pay back its customers or lenders,=C2=A0and implodes.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">But it had $0 worth of stuff, so this seems like a pr=
etty reasonable result, though of course bad for customers.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In other words, every crypto liquidity crisis =
story that I have heard is=C2=A0<em>obviously a solvency crisis</em>. The p=
roblem is not that the firm has good assets but cannot, for some reason, co=
nvert them quickly into ready money. The problem is that the firm has bad a=
ssets and people notice and demand their money back and the money isn=E2=80=
=99t there. The reasons the money isn=E2=80=99t there will vary. Sometimes =
the firm just lost money on risky trades. Sometimes the money all went into=
 magic beans and the magic bean market collapsed. (This is the story of <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29707590.273527/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTEvdGVycmEt=
ZmxvcHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTExNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0f69ddd5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  TerraUSD and Luna</a>.) Sometim=
es the money was stolen by hackers, or by the firm=E2=80=99s executives, or=
 both.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the story is never =E2=80=9Cthis crypto fi=
rm took demand deposits and used them to fund 30-year mortgages, and while =
those mortgages are still paying and are likely to be money-good, the firm =
doesn=E2=80=99t have the cash right now.=E2=80=9D Because that is, uh, not =
really how crypto works? Compared to banks, crypto firms probably have a bi=
t more carelessness and fraud, but they=C2=A0<em>definitely=C2=A0</em>have =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29707590.273527/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cudG9kYXlpbnRhYnMuY29tL3AvbWFnaWMtYmVhbi1kYWQ/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB3e9fe1d6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> a lot more magic beans</a>. Crypto firms tend to=
 have assets that do not have cash flows, and that are highly correlated to=
=C2=A0<em>confidence in crypto=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0often highly correl=
ated to=C2=A0<em>confidence in that firm itself=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0an=
d so when they lose confidence they also tend to lose their assets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/29707590.273527/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9jel9iaW5hbmNlL=
3N0YXR1cy8xNTkyMDQ0NDk2MTc0NjEyNDgy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe76e2087" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;"> here=E2=80=99s a tweet</a> from Changpeng =E2=80=9CCZ=E2=80=9D Zhao, t=
he chief executive officer of Binance Holdings Ltd.:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To reduce further cascading negati=
ve effects of FTX, Binance is forming an industry recovery fund, to help pr=
ojects who are otherwise strong, but in a liquidity crisis. More details to=
 come soon. In the meantime, please contact Binance Labs if you think you q=
ualify.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The most notable liquidity crisis in crypto th=
is year was at FTX.com, the big crypto exchange founded by Sam Bankman-Frie=
d. And when FTX needed money for customer withdrawals, it <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29707590.273527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDgvYmluYW5jZS1zLXpoYW8tc2=
JmLWVkLWZ0eC1zLWJhbmttYW4tZnJpZWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTExNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX=
21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTE1JnV0bV9j=
YW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd18904b5" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  went =
to Binance for a bailout</a>. And Binance agreed to rescue FTX, subject to =
due diligence. And then Binance did like 15 minutes of due diligence and <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29707590.273527/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmFua21=
hbi1mcmllZC1zLWZ0eC1oYWQtYS1kZWF0aC1zcGlyYWwtYmVmb3JlLWJpbmFuY2UtZGVhbD9jbX=
BpZD1CQkQxMTE1MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c=
2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExMTUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB89b6b4fa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">  said absolutely not</a>, and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29707590.273527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTAvZnR4LWlzLXN0aWxsLW=
xvb2tpbmctZm9yLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMTUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09Z=
W1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTExNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249=
bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB91326540" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  the deal fell a=
part</a>. Because it is pretty obvious that FTX is not =E2=80=9Cotherwise s=
trong, but in a liquidity crisis=E2=80=9D: FTX is in a <em>solvency </em>cr=
isis, in which the customer money is mostly gone and <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29707590.273527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTQvZnR4LXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC1=
3YXMtYmFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMTUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3=
NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTExNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZ=
g/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfe14315e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  what=E2=80=99s left is mostl=
y worthless beans</a>.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Several of the other most notable liquidity cr=
ises in crypto this year were at firms that were themselves bailed out by F=
TX and Alameda Research, a hedge fund that was also founded by Bankman-Frie=
d and that was closely associated with FTX. For whatever reason, FTX and Al=
ameda do not seem to have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/29707590.273527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjItMDctMTkvYmFua21hbi1mcmllZC1zYXlzLWNyeXB0by13aW50ZXItc2hpZnRzLWludm=
VzdG9yLWZvY3VzLXRvLXByb2ZpdD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTE1MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVka=
XVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExMTUmdXRtX2NhbXBh=
aWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb21aa9f9" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  concerned =
themselves too much</a> with whether the firms they were rescuing were solv=
ent.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is possible that over the next few years th=
ere will be a Binance-led industry recovery fund, and it will act like a ce=
ntral bank for crypto, and it will lend freely, against good collateral, at=
 penalty rates. And occasionally, in challenging markets, crypto projects t=
hat are otherwise strong, but in a liquidity crisis, will come to the Centr=
al Binance Bank to borrow money, and the Central Binance Bank will support =
them, and they will preserve long-term value. But if the Central Binance Ba=
nk had existed=C2=A0<em>this=C2=A0</em>year, how many projects would it hav=
e saved? Not FTX, anyway.</p>
