xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here is =
a paper</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0which shares three of its four authors with the =
powerful-sports-car one =E2=80=94=C2=A0about how =E2=80=9Cmutual fund manag=
ers increase investment allocations to companies manufacturing automobiles =
they have purchased.=E2=80=9D If you drive a Ferrari you will take more ris=
k for fewer returns; if you drive a Ford you=E2=80=99ll buy stock in Ford. =
Also:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We then examine why fund managers tend to over=
weight companies whose products they consume and find satisfactory in their=
 portfolio. Among retail investors, a leading explanation that has been pro=
posed in=C2=A0 the literature is behavioral biases related to familiarity o=
r preferences. =E2=80=A6 Among professional investors, however, it would be=
 surprising if this investment pattern is driven by the familiarity/prefere=
nce bias, since these investors face higher costs from poor portfolio perfo=
rmance due, for example, to career concerns (Chevalier and Ellison, 1999b).=
 As an alternative, we propose that consumption experiences contain value-r=
elevant information, which may serve as the basis for consumption-induced p=
ortfolio choices among investment fiduciaries. =E2=80=A6 Fortunately, these=
 two channels (familiarity vs. informational advantage) can be empirically =
disentangled by examining the performance of post-consumption positions, as=
 the two channels lead to different performance implications. The familiari=
ty/preference bias explanation predicts that consumption-induced positions =
should perform similarly to, if not worse than, other positions; the inform=
ation-based explanation, on the other hand, predicts that these positions s=
hould have superior performance.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Consistent with the information-based explanat=
ion, we find that after an automobile purchase, fund-managers=E2=80=99 posi=
tions in companies manufacturing the purchased automobiles can better predi=
ct these manufacturers=E2=80=99 future stock returns.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you drive a Ford and then buy Ford stock, y=
ou probably have a good reason, and the stock will go up. Somehow the paper=
 does not mention Tesla.</p>
